[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] If ⁠ $\textstyle \alpha \in \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ ⁠, then $\alpha$ is said to be a ***k*-vector**.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] If, furthermore, $\alpha$ can be expressed as an exterior product of k elements of ⁠ V ⁠, then $\alpha$ is said to be **decomposable** (or **simple**, by some authors; or a **blade**, by others).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Although decomposable ⁠ k ⁠-vectors span ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ ⁠, not every element of $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ is decomposable.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] is a basis for ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] every vector $v_{j}$ can be written as a linear combination of the basis vectors ⁠ $e_{i}$ ⁠; using the bilinearity of the exterior product, this can be expanded to a linear combination of exterior products of those basis vectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Any exterior product in which the same basis vector appears more than once is zero; any exterior product in which the basis vectors do not appear in the proper order can be reordered, changing the sign whenever two basis vectors change places.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In general, the resulting coefficients of the basis k-vectors can be computed as the minors of the matrix that describes the vectors $v_{j}$ in terms of the basis ⁠ $e_{i}$ ⁠.
