[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The binomial coefficient produces the correct result, even for exceptional cases; in particular, $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)=\{0\}$ for ⁠ $k>n$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Any element of the exterior algebra can be written as a sum of *k*-vectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] (where, by convention, ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!0}(V)=K$ ⁠, the field underlying ⁠ V ⁠, and ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!1}(V)=V$ ⁠), and therefore its dimension is equal to the sum of the binomial coefficients, which is ⁠ $2^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The **rank** of the *k*-vector $\alpha$ is the minimal number of decomposable *k*-vectors in such an expansion of ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This is similar to the notion of tensor rank.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Rank is particularly important in the study of 2-vectors (Sternberg 1964, §III.6) (Bryant et al.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The rank of a 2-vector $\alpha$ can be identified with half the rank of the matrix of coefficients of $\alpha$ in a basis.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] where $a_{ij}=-a_{ji}$ (the matrix of coefficients is skew-symmetric).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The rank of the matrix $a_{ij}$ is therefore even, and is twice the rank of the form $\alpha$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The exterior product of a *k*-vector with a *p*-vector is a $(k+p)$ -vector, once again invoking bilinearity.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In addition to studying the graded structure on the exterior algebra, Bourbaki (1989) studies additional graded structures on exterior algebras, such as those on the exterior algebra of a graded module (a module that already carries its own gradation).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Let V be a vector space over the field K .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Informally, multiplication in $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ is performed by manipulating symbols and imposing a distributive law, an associative law, and using the identity $v\wedge v=0$ for $v\in V$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Formally, $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ is the "most general" algebra in which these rules hold for the multiplication, in the sense that any unital associative K -algebra containing V with alternating multiplication on V must contain a homomorphic image of $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] To construct the most general algebra that contains V and whose multiplication is alternating on V , it is natural to start with the most general associative algebra that contains V , the tensor algebra $T(V)$ , and then enforce the alternating property by taking a suitable quotient.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] (and use $\wedge$ as the symbol for multiplication in $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ ).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] It is then straightforward to show that $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ contains V and satisfies the above universal property.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] As a consequence of this construction, the operation of assigning to a vector space V its exterior algebra $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ is a functor from the category of vector spaces to the category of algebras.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Rather than defining $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ first and then identifying the exterior powers $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ as certain subspaces, one may alternatively define the spaces $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ first and then combine them to form the algebra $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This approach is often used in differential geometry and is described in the next section.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Given a commutative ring R and an R -module ⁠ M ⁠, we can define the exterior algebra $\textstyle \bigwedge (M)$ just as above, as a suitable quotient of the tensor algebra ⁠ $\mathrm {T} (M)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] It will satisfy the analogous universal property.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Many of the properties of $\textstyle \bigwedge (M)$ also require that M be a projective module.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Where finite dimensionality is used, the properties further require that M be finitely generated and projective.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Generalizations to the most common situations can be found in Bourbaki (1989).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Exterior algebras of vector bundles are frequently considered in geometry and topology.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] There are no essential differences between the algebraic properties of the exterior algebra of finite-dimensional vector bundles and those of the exterior algebra of finitely generated projective modules, by the Serre–Swan theorem.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] More general exterior algebras can be defined for sheaves of modules.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] For a field of characteristic not 2, the exterior algebra of a vector space V over K can be canonically identified with the vector subspace of $\mathrm {T} (V)$ that consists of antisymmetric tensors.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] For characteristic 0 (or higher than ⁠ $\dim V$ ⁠), the vector space of k -linear antisymmetric tensors is transversal to the ideal ⁠ I ⁠, hence, a good choice to represent the quotient.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Of course, for characteristic ⁠ 0 ⁠ (or higher than the dimension of the vector space), one or the other definition of the product could be used, as the two algebras are isomorphic (see V.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Let $\mathrm {T} ^{r}(V)$ be the space of homogeneous tensors of degree r .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] where the sum is taken over the symmetric group of permutations on the symbols ⁠ $\{1,\dots ,r\}$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This extends by linearity and homogeneity to an operation, also denoted by ${\mathcal {A}}$ and ${\rm {Alt}}$ , on the full tensor algebra ⁠ $\mathrm {T} (V)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Such that, when defined, $\operatorname {Alt} ^{(r)}$ is the projection for the exterior (quotient) algebra onto the r-homogeneous alternating tensor subspace.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] On the other hand, the image ${\mathcal {A}}(\mathrm {T} (V))$ is always the **alternating tensor graded subspace** (not yet an algebra, as product is not yet defined), denoted ⁠ $A(V)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This is a vector subspace of ⁠ $\mathrm {T} (V)$ ⁠, and it inherits the structure of a graded vector space from that on ⁠ $\mathrm {T} (V)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Moreover, the kernel of ${\mathcal {A}}^{(r)}$ is precisely ⁠ $I^{(r)}$ ⁠, the homogeneous subset of the ideal ⁠ I ⁠, or the kernel of ${\mathcal {A}}$ is ⁠ I ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] When the characteristic of the field is nonzero, ${\mathcal {A}}$ will do what ${\rm {Alt}}$ did before, but the product cannot be defined as above.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In such a case, isomorphism $\textstyle A(V)\cong \bigwedge (V)$ still holds, in spite of $A(V)$ not being a supplement of the ideal ⁠ I ⁠, but then, the product should be modified as given below ( ${\dot {\wedge }}$ product, Arnold setting).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Finally, we always get ⁠ $A(V)$ ⁠ isomorphic with ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ ⁠, but the product could (or should) be chosen in two ways (or only one).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Actually, the product could be chosen in many ways, rescaling it on homogeneous spaces as $c(r+p)/c(r)c(p)$ for an arbitrary sequence $c(r)$ in the field, as long as the division makes sense (this is such that the redefined product is also associative, i.e. defines an algebra on ⁠ $A(V)$ ⁠).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Also note, the interior product definition should be changed accordingly, in order to keep its skew derivation property.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Suppose that *V* has finite dimension *n*, and that a basis **e**1, ..., **e***n* of *V* is given.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] where *t**i*1⋅⋅⋅*i**r* is completely antisymmetric in its indices.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The interior product may also be described in index notation as follows.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] which associates to k vectors from V their exterior product, i.e. their corresponding k -vector, is also alternating.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The above discussion specializes to the case when ⁠ $X=K$ ⁠, the base field.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] is called an **alternating multilinear form**.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The set of all alternating multilinear forms is a vector space, as the sum of two such maps, or the product of such a map with a scalar, is again alternating.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] By the universal property of the exterior power, the space of alternating forms of degree k on V is naturally isomorphic with the dual vector space ⁠ $\textstyle {\bigl (}{\bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)}{\bigr )}^{*}$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] If V is finite-dimensional, then the latter is naturally isomorphic to ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V^{*})$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In particular, if V is n -dimensional, the dimension of the space of alternating maps from $V^{k}$ to K is the binomial coefficient ⁠ $\textstyle {\binom {n}{k}}$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Under such identification, the exterior product takes a concrete form: it produces a new anti-symmetric map from two given ones.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Suppose ⁠ $\textstyle \omega \colon V^{k}\to K$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\textstyle \eta \colon V^{m}\to K$ ⁠ are two anti-symmetric maps.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] As in the case of tensor products of multilinear maps, the number of variables of their exterior product is the sum of the numbers of their variables.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] As this might look very specific and fine tuned, an equivalent raw version is to sum in the above formula over permutations in left cosets of *S**k*+*m* / (*S**k* × *S**m*).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This derivation is called the **interior product** with ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠, or sometimes the **insertion operator**, or **contraction** by ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Suppose that ⁠ $\textstyle w\in \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Then w is a multilinear mapping of $V^{*}$ to ⁠ K ⁠, so it is defined by its values on the k -fold Cartesian product ⁠ $V^{*}\times V^{*}\times \dots \times V^{*}$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Additionally, let $\iota _{\alpha }f=0$ whenever f is a pure scalar (i.e., belonging to ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!0}(V)$ ⁠).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] If v is an element of V (⁠ $\textstyle =\bigwedge ^{\!1}(V)$ ⁠), then ⁠ $\iota _{\alpha }v=\alpha (v)$ ⁠ is the dual pairing between elements of V and elements of ⁠ $V^{*}$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] These three properties are sufficient to characterize the interior product as well as define it in the general infinite-dimensional case.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Suppose that V has finite dimension ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In the geometrical setting, a non-zero element of the top exterior power ${\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!n}}(V)$ (which is a one-dimensional vector space) is sometimes called a **volume form** (or **orientation form**, although this term may sometimes lead to ambiguity).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The name orientation form comes from the fact that a choice of preferred top element determines an orientation of the whole exterior algebra, since it is tantamount to fixing an ordered basis of the vector space.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The composition of $\star$ with itself maps $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)\to \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ and is always a scalar multiple of the identity map.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In most applications, the volume form is compatible with the inner product in the sense that it is an exterior product of an orthonormal basis of ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] where id is the identity mapping, and the inner product has metric signature (*p*, *q*) — *p* pluses and *q* minuses.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] For ⁠ V ⁠ a finite-dimensional space, an inner product (or a pseudo-Euclidean inner product) on ⁠ V ⁠ defines an isomorphism of V with ⁠ $V^{*}$ ⁠, and so also an isomorphism of $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ with ⁠ $\textstyle {\bigl (}{\bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)}{\bigr )}^{*}$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The pairing between these two spaces also takes the form of an inner product.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] the determinant of the matrix of inner products.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In the special case *v**i* = *w**i*, the inner product is the square norm of the *k*-vector, given by the determinant of the Gramian matrix (⟨*v**i*, *v**j*⟩).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This is then extended bilinearly (or sesquilinearly in the complex case) to a non-degenerate inner product on ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] constitute an orthonormal basis for ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ ⁠, a statement equivalent to the Cauchy–Binet formula.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] With respect to the inner product, exterior multiplication and the interior product are mutually adjoint.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This property completely characterizes the inner product on the exterior algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] There is a correspondence between the graded dual of the graded algebra $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ and alternating multilinear forms on ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The exterior algebra (as well as the symmetric algebra) inherits a bialgebra structure, and, indeed, a Hopf algebra structure, from the tensor algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] See the article on tensor algebras for a detailed treatment of the topic.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The exterior product of multilinear forms defined above is dual to a coproduct defined on ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ ⁠, giving the structure of a coalgebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The symbol 1 stands for the unit element of the field ⁠ K ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Recall that ⁠ $\textstyle K\simeq \bigwedge ^{\!0}(V)\subseteq \bigwedge (V)$ ⁠, so that the above really does lie in ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)\otimes \bigwedge (V)$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This definition of the coproduct is lifted to the full space $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ by (linear) homomorphism.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The correct form of this homomorphism is not what one might naively write, but has to be the one carefully defined in the coalgebra article.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] where the second summation is taken over all (*p*, *k*−*p*)-shuffles.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] It is also convenient to take the pure wedge products $v_{\sigma (1)}\wedge \dots \wedge v_{\sigma (p)}$ and $v_{\sigma (p+1)}\wedge \dots \wedge v_{\sigma (k)}$ to equal 1 for *p* = 0 and *p* = *k*, respectively (the empty product in $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ ).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The shuffle follows directly from the first axiom of a co-algebra: the relative order of the elements $x_{k}$ is *preserved* in the riffle shuffle: the riffle shuffle merely splits the ordered sequence into two ordered sequences, one on the left, and one on the right.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Observe that the coproduct preserves the grading of the algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The tensor symbol $\otimes$ used in this section should be understood with some caution: it is *not* the same tensor symbol as the one being used in the definition of the alternating product.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Any lingering doubt can be shaken by pondering the equalities $(1\otimes v)\wedge (1\otimes w)=1\otimes (v\wedge w)$ and $(v\otimes 1)\wedge (1\otimes w)=v\otimes w$ , which follow from the definition of the coalgebra, as opposed to naive manipulations involving the tensor and wedge symbols.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] This distinction is developed in greater detail in the article on tensor algebras.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Here, there is much less of a problem, in that the alternating product $\wedge$ clearly corresponds to multiplication in the exterior algebra, leaving the symbol $\otimes$ free for use in the definition of the bialgebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In practice, this presents no particular problem, as long as one avoids the fatal trap of replacing alternating sums of $\otimes$ by the wedge symbol, with one exception.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] One can construct an alternating product from $\otimes$ , with the understanding that it works in a different space.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Immediately below, an example is given: the alternating product for the *dual space* can be given in terms of the coproduct.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The construction of the bialgebra here parallels the construction in the tensor algebra article almost exactly, except for the need to correctly track the alternating signs for the exterior algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] where the tensor product on the right-hand side is of multilinear linear maps (extended by zero on elements of incompatible homogeneous degree: more precisely, $\alpha \wedge \beta =\varepsilon \circ (\alpha \otimes \beta )\circ \Delta$ , where $\varepsilon$ is the counit, as defined presently).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The **counit** is the homomorphism $\textstyle \varepsilon \colon \bigwedge (V)\to K$ that returns the 0-graded component of its argument.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The coproduct and counit, along with the exterior product, define the structure of a bialgebra on the exterior algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] With an **antipode** defined on homogeneous elements by ⁠ $S(x)=(-1)^{\binom {{\text{deg}}\,x\,+1}{2}}x$ ⁠, the exterior algebra is furthermore a Hopf algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] Suppose that V and W are a pair of vector spaces and $f\colon V\to W$ is a linear map.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In particular, ${\textstyle \bigwedge }(f)$ preserves homogeneous degree.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] The components of the transformation ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(f)$ ⁠ relative to a basis of V and W is the matrix of $k\times k$ minors of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p01] In particular, if $V=W$ and V is of finite dimension ⁠ n ⁠, then $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!n}(f)$ is a mapping of a one-dimensional vector space $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!n}(V)$ to itself, and is therefore given by a scalar: the determinant of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The natural setting for (oriented) k -dimensional volume and exterior algebra is affine space.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] This is also the intimate connection between exterior algebra and differential forms, as to integrate we need a 'differential' object to measure infinitesimal volume.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional space, the volume of any n -dimensional simplex is a scalar multiple of any other.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The sum of the $(k-1)$ -dimensional oriented areas of the boundary simplexes of a ⁠ k ⁠-dimensional simplex is zero, as for the sum of vectors around a triangle or the oriented triangles bounding the tetrahedron in the previous section.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The vector space structure on $\textstyle \bigwedge (V)$ generalises addition of vectors in ⁠ V ⁠: we have $(u_{1}+u_{2})\wedge v=u_{1}\wedge v+u_{2}\wedge v$ and similarly a *k*-blade $v_{1}\wedge \dots \wedge v_{k}$ is linear in each factor.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In applications to linear algebra, the exterior product provides an abstract algebraic manner for describing the determinant and the minors of a matrix.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] For instance, it is well known that the determinant of a square matrix is equal to the volume of the parallelotope whose sides are the columns of the matrix (with a sign to track orientation).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] This suggests that the determinant can be *defined* in terms of the exterior product of the column vectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Likewise, the *k* × *k* minors of a matrix can be defined by looking at the exterior products of column vectors chosen *k* at a time.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] These ideas can be extended not just to matrices but to linear transformations as well: the determinant of a linear transformation is the factor by which it scales the oriented volume of any given reference parallelotope.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] So the determinant of a linear transformation can be defined in terms of what the transformation does to the top exterior power.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The action of a transformation on the lesser exterior powers gives a basis-independent way to talk about the minors of the transformation.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In physics, many quantities are naturally represented by alternating operators.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] For example, if the motion of a charged particle is described by velocity and acceleration vectors in four-dimensional spacetime, then normalization of the velocity vector requires that the electromagnetic force must be an alternating operator on the velocity.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Its six degrees of freedom are identified with the electric and magnetic fields.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In Einstein's theories of relativity, the electromagnetic field is generally given as a differential 2-form $F=dA$ in 4-space or as the equivalent alternating tensor field $F_{ij}=A_{[i,j]}=A_{[i;j]},$ the electromagnetic tensor.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Then $dF=ddA=0$ or the equivalent Bianchi identity $F_{[ij,k]}=F_{[ij;k]}=0.$ None of this requires a metric.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The decomposable *k*-vectors have geometric interpretations: the bivector $u\wedge v$ represents the plane spanned by the vectors, "weighted" with a number, given by the area of the oriented parallelogram with sides u and ⁠ v ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Analogously, the 3-vector $u\wedge v\wedge w$ represents the spanned 3-space weighted by the volume of the oriented parallelepiped with edges ⁠ u ⁠, ⁠ v ⁠, and ⁠ w ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Decomposable *k*-vectors in $\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}(V)$ correspond to weighted *k*-dimensional linear subspaces of ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In particular, the Grassmannian of *k*-dimensional subspaces of ⁠ V ⁠, denoted ⁠ $\operatorname {Gr} _{k}(V)$ ⁠, can be naturally identified with an algebraic subvariety of the projective space $\textstyle \mathbf {P} {\bigl (}\bigwedge ^{\!k}(V){\bigr )}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] This is called the Plücker embedding, and the image of the embedding can be characterized by the Plücker relations.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The exterior algebra has notable applications in differential geometry, where it is used to define differential forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] A differential form at a point of a differentiable manifold is an alternating multilinear form on the tangent space at the point.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Equivalently, a differential form of degree *k* is a linear functional on the *k*th exterior power of the tangent space.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] As a consequence, the exterior product of multilinear forms defines a natural exterior product for differential forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Differential forms play a major role in diverse areas of differential geometry.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] An alternate approach defines differential forms in terms of germs of functions.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In particular, the exterior derivative gives the exterior algebra of differential forms on a manifold the structure of a differential graded algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The exterior derivative commutes with pullback along smooth mappings between manifolds, and it is therefore a natural differential operator.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The exterior algebra of differential forms, equipped with the exterior derivative, is a cochain complex whose cohomology is called the de Rham cohomology of the underlying manifold and plays a vital role in the algebraic topology of differentiable manifolds.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In representation theory, the exterior algebra is one of the two fundamental Schur functors on the category of vector spaces, the other being the symmetric algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Together, these constructions are used to generate the irreducible representations of the general linear group (see *Fundamental representation*).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The exterior algebra over the complex numbers is the archetypal example of a superalgebra, which plays a fundamental role in physical theories pertaining to fermions and supersymmetry.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] A single element of the exterior algebra is called a **supernumber** or Grassmann number.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The exterior algebra itself is then just a one-dimensional superspace: it is just the set of all of the points in the exterior algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The topology on this space is essentially the weak topology, the open sets being the cylinder sets.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] An *n*-dimensional superspace is just the ⁠ n ⁠-fold product of exterior algebras.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Let L be a Lie algebra over a field ⁠ K ⁠, then it is possible to define the structure of a chain complex on the exterior algebra of ⁠ L ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The Jacobi identity holds if and only if ⁠ ${1}$ ⁠, and so this is a necessary and sufficient condition for an anticommutative nonassociative algebra L to be a Lie algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Moreover, in that case $\textstyle \bigwedge (L)$ is a chain complex with boundary operator ⁠ $\partial$ ⁠.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The homology associated to this complex is the Lie algebra homology.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The exterior algebra is the main ingredient in the construction of the Koszul complex, a fundamental object in homological algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The exterior algebra was first introduced by Hermann Grassmann in 1844 under the blanket term of *Ausdehnungslehre*, or *Theory of Extension*.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] This referred more generally to an algebraic (or axiomatic) theory of extended quantities and was one of the early precursors to the modern notion of a vector space.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Saint-Venant also published similar ideas of exterior calculus for which he claimed priority over Grassmann.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The algebra itself was built from a set of rules, or axioms, capturing the formal aspects of Cayley and Sylvester's theory of multivectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] It was thus a *calculus*, much like the propositional calculus, except focused exclusively on the task of formal reasoning in geometrical terms.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] In particular, this new development allowed for an *axiomatic* characterization of dimension, a property that had previously only been examined from the coordinate point of view.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] The import of this new theory of vectors and multivectors was lost to mid-19th-century mathematicians, until being thoroughly vetted by Giuseppe Peano in 1888.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] Peano's work also remained somewhat obscure until the turn of the century, when the subject was unified by members of the French geometry school (notably Henri Poincaré, Élie Cartan, and Gaston Darboux) who applied Grassmann's ideas to the calculus of differential forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] A short while later, Alfred North Whitehead, borrowing from the ideas of Peano and Grassmann, introduced his universal algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-algebra-p02] This then paved the way for the 20th-century developments of abstract algebra by placing the axiomatic notion of an algebraic system on a firm logical footing.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] On a differentiable manifold, the **exterior derivative** extends the concept of the differential of a function to differential forms of higher degree.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The exterior derivative was first described in its current form by Élie Cartan in 1899.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The resulting calculus, known as exterior calculus, allows for a natural, metric-independent generalization of Stokes' theorem, Gauss's theorem, and Green's theorem from vector calculus.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] If a differential k -form is thought of as measuring the flux through an infinitesimal k -parallelotope at each point of the manifold, then its exterior derivative can be thought of as measuring the net flux through the boundary of a $(k+1)$ -parallelotope at each point.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The exterior derivative of a differential form of degree k (also differential k -form, or just k -form for brevity here) is a differential form of degree $k+1$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] If f is a smooth function (a 0 -form), then the exterior derivative of f is the differential of f .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] That is, $df$ is the unique 1-form such that for every smooth vector field X , $df(X)=d_{X}f$ , where $d_{X}f$ is the directional derivative of f in the direction of X .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The exterior product of differential forms (denoted with the same symbol $\wedge$ ) is defined as their pointwise exterior product.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] There are a variety of equivalent definitions of the exterior derivative of a general k -form.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] If f and g are two 0 -forms (functions), then from the third property for the quantity $d(f\wedge g)$ , which is simply $d(fg)$ , the familiar product rule $d(fg)=g\,df+f\,dg$ is recovered.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Alternatively, one can work entirely in a local coordinate system $(x^{1},\ldots ,x^{n})$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The coordinate differentials ${\text{d}}x^{1},\ldots ,{\text{d}}x^{n}$ form a basis of the space of one-forms, each associated with a coordinate.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The definition of the exterior derivative is extended linearly to a general k -form (which is expressible as a linear combination of basic simple k -forms) $\omega =f_{I}\,dx^{I},$ where each of the components of the multi-index I run over all the values in $\{1,\ldots ,n\}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Note that whenever j equals one of the components of the multi-index I then ${\text{d}}x^{j}\wedge {\text{d}}x^{I}=0$ (see *Exterior product*).
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The definition of the exterior derivative in local coordinates follows from the preceding definition in terms of axioms.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Here, we have interpreted g as a 0 -form, and then applied the properties of the exterior derivative.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The last formula, where summation starts at $i=3$ , follows easily from the properties of the exterior product.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Intuitively, if one thinks of M as being divided into infinitesimal regions, and one adds the flux through the boundaries of all the regions, the interior boundaries all cancel out, leaving the total flux through the boundary of M .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] A k -form $\omega$ is called *closed* if $d\omega =0$ ; closed forms are the kernel of d . $\omega$ is called *exact* if $\omega =d\alpha$ for some $(k-1)$ -form $\alpha$ ; exact forms are the image of d .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Because $d^{2}=0$ , every exact form is closed.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The Poincaré lemma states that in a contractible region, the converse is true.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Because the exterior derivative d has the property that $d^{2}=0$ , it can be used as the differential (coboundary) to define de Rham cohomology on a manifold.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The k -th de Rham cohomology (group) is the vector space of closed k -forms modulo the exact k -forms; as noted in the previous section, the Poincaré lemma states that these vector spaces are trivial for a contractible region, for $k>0$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] For smooth manifolds, integration of forms gives a natural homomorphism from the de Rham cohomology to the singular cohomology over $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The theorem of de Rham shows that this map is actually an isomorphism, a far-reaching generalization of the Poincaré lemma.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] As suggested by the generalized Stokes' theorem, the exterior derivative is the "dual" of the boundary map on singular simplices.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] This follows from that $f^{*}\omega (\cdot )$ , by definition, is $\omega (f_{*}(\cdot ))$ , $f_{*}$ being the pushforward of f .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Thus d is a natural transformation from $\Omega ^{k}$ to $\Omega ^{k+1}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Most vector calculus operators are special cases of, or have close relationships to, the notion of exterior differentiation.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] A smooth function $f:M\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ on a real differentiable manifold M is a 0 -form.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The exterior derivative of this 0 -form is the 1 -form $df$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] That is, $\nabla f=(df)^{\sharp }=\sum _{i=1}^{n}{\frac {\partial f}{\partial x^{i}}}\,\left(dx^{i}\right)^{\sharp },$ where $\sharp$ denotes the musical isomorphism $\sharp :V^{*}\rightarrow V$ mentioned earlier that is induced by the inner product.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The 1 -form $df$ is a section of the cotangent bundle, that gives a local linear approximation to f in the cotangent space at each point.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] (For instance, when $n=3$ , i.e. in three-dimensional space, the 2 -form $\omega _{V}$ is locally the scalar triple product with V .) The integral of $\omega _{V}$ over a hypersurface is the flux of V over that hypersurface.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Locally, $\eta _{V}$ is the dot product with V .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] The integral of $\eta _{V}$ along a path is the work done against $-V$ along that path.
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] Note that the expression for $\operatorname {curl}$ requires $\sharp$ to act on $\star d(F^{\flat })$ , which is a form of degree $n-2$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/exterior-derivative] A natural generalization of $\sharp$ to k -forms of arbitrary degree allows this expression to make sense for any n .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] In mathematics, the **Hodge star operator** or **Hodge star** is a linear map defined on the exterior algebra of a finite-dimensional oriented vector space endowed with a nondegenerate symmetric bilinear form.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Applying the operator to an element of the algebra produces the **Hodge dual** of the element.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Generalizing this to an n -dimensional vector space, the Hodge star is a one-to-one mapping of k -vectors to $(n-k)$ -vectors; the dimensions of these spaces are the binomial coefficients ${\tbinom {n}{k}}={\tbinom {n}{n-k}}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The naturality of the star operator means it can play a role in differential geometry when applied to the cotangent bundle of a pseudo-Riemannian manifold, and hence to differential *k*-forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] This allows the definition of the codifferential as the Hodge adjoint of the exterior derivative, leading to the Laplace–de Rham operator.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] This generalizes the case of 3-dimensional Euclidean space, in which divergence of a vector field may be realized as the codifferential opposite to the gradient operator, and the Laplace operator on a function is the divergence of its gradient.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] An important application is the Hodge decomposition of differential forms on a closed Riemannian manifold.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Let *V* be an *n*-dimensional oriented vector space with a symmetric bilinear form $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ , referred to here as an inner product.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] extended to ${\textstyle \bigwedge ^{\!k}V}$ through linearity.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] where the sign is free to be chosen and fixed as plus or minus.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The **Hodge star operator** is a linear operator on the exterior algebra of *V*, mapping *k*-vectors to (*n*–*k*)-vectors, for $0\leq k\leq n$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] which applies the Gram matrix and takes the right complement.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] where the tilde denotes the reverse operation, and *I* is the volume element, or pseudoscalar.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] There is a left version of the Hodge dual that can have per-grade sign differences compared to the right version defined above in even numbers of dimensions.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] When a distinction needs to be made, the right Hodge dual is often denoted by a superscript star such that $\alpha ^{\bigstar }={\overline {G\alpha }}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] where the underline takes the *left complement* satisfying ${\underline {m}}\wedge m=\omega$ for any basis element m .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] When the bilinear form is nondegenerate, the Hodge star operator takes an orthonormal basis to an orthonormal basis.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] In this case, it is an isometry on the exterior algebra ${\textstyle \bigwedge V}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The Hodge star is motivated by the correspondence between a subspace *W* of *V* and its orthogonal subspace (with respect to the scalar product), where each space is endowed with an orientation and a numerical scaling factor.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] where $u_{1},\ldots ,u_{n-k}$ form an oriented basis of the orthogonal space $U=W^{\perp }\!$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Furthermore, the (*n* − *k*)-volume of the $u_{i}$ -parallelepiped must equal the *k*-volume of the $w_{i}$ -parallelepiped, and $w_{1},\ldots ,w_{k},u_{1},\ldots ,u_{n-k}$ must form an oriented basis of V .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] A general *k*-vector is a linear combination of decomposable *k*-vectors, and the definition of Hodge star is extended to general *k*-vectors by defining it as being linear.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] A common example of the Hodge star operator is the case *n* = 3, when it can be taken as the correspondence between vectors and bivectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The Hodge star can also be interpreted as a form of the geometric correspondence between an axis of rotation and an infinitesimal rotation (see also: 3D rotation group#Lie algebra) around the axis, with speed equal to the length of the axis of rotation.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] A scalar product on a vector space V gives an isomorphism $V\cong V^{*}\!$ identifying V with its dual space, and the vector space $L(V,V)$ is naturally isomorphic to the tensor product $V^{*}\!\!\otimes V\cong V\otimes V$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Thus for $V=\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , the star mapping ${\textstyle \textstyle {\star }:V\to \bigwedge ^{\!2}\!V\subset V\otimes V}$ takes each vector $\mathbf {v}$ to a bivector ${\star }\mathbf {v} \in V\otimes V$ , which corresponds to a linear operator $L_{\mathbf {v} }:V\to V$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Specifically, $L_{\mathbf {v} }$ is a skew-symmetric operator, which corresponds to an infinitesimal rotation: that is, the macroscopic rotations around the axis $\mathbb {v}$ are given by the matrix exponential $\exp(tL_{\mathbf {v} })$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] In case $n=4$ , the Hodge star acts as an endomorphism of the second exterior power (i.e. it maps 2-forms to 2-forms, since 4 − 2 = 2).
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] If the signature of the metric tensor is all positive, i.e. on a Riemannian manifold, then the Hodge star is an involution.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] If the signature is mixed, i.e., pseudo-Riemannian, then applying the operator twice will return the argument up to a sign – see *§ Duality* below.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] This particular endomorphism property of 2-forms in four dimensions makes self-dual and anti-self-dual two-forms natural geometric objects to study.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] That is, one can describe the space of 2-forms in four dimensions with a basis that "diagonalizes" the Hodge star operator with eigenvalues $\pm 1$ (or $\pm i$ , depending on the signature).
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] For concreteness, we discuss the Hodge star operator in Minkowski spacetime where $n=4$ with metric signature (− + + +) and coordinates $(t,x,y,z)$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The volume form is oriented as $\varepsilon _{0123}=1$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Hodge dual of three- and four-forms can be easily deduced from the fact that, in the Lorentzian signature, ${\star }^{2}=1$ for odd-rank forms and ${\star }^{2}=-1$ for even-rank forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] An easy rule to remember for these Hodge operations is that given a form $\alpha$ , its Hodge dual ${\star }\alpha$ may be obtained by writing the components not involved in $\alpha$ in an order such that $\alpha \wedge ({\star }\alpha )=dt\wedge dx\wedge dy\wedge dz$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] An extra minus sign will enter only if $\alpha$ contains $dt$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The Hodge star is conformally invariant on *n*-forms on a 2*n*-dimensional vector space V , i.e. if g is a metric on V and $\lambda >0$ , then the induced Hodge stars ${\star }_{g},{\star }_{\lambda g}:\Lambda ^{n}V\to \Lambda ^{n}V$ are the same.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The combination of the ${\star }$ operator and the exterior derivative *d* generates the classical operators grad, curl, and div on vector fields in three-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] This works out as follows: *d* takes a 0-form (a function) to a 1-form, a 1-form to a 2-form, and a 2-form to a 3-form (and takes a 3-form to zero).
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The scalar product identifies 1-forms with vector fields as $dx\mapsto (1,0,0)$ , etc., so that $df$ becomes ${\textstyle \operatorname {grad} f=\left({\frac {\partial f}{\partial x}},{\frac {\partial f}{\partial y}},{\frac {\partial f}{\partial z}}\right)}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] In the third case, $\mathbf {F} =(A,B,C)$ again corresponds to $\varphi =A\,dx+B\,dy+C\,dz$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] One advantage of this expression is that the identity *d*2 = 0, which is true in all cases, has as special cases two other identities: (1) curl grad *f* = 0, and (2) div curl **F** = 0.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] In particular, Maxwell's equations take on a particularly simple and elegant form, when expressed in terms of the exterior derivative and the Hodge star.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The expression ${\star }d{\star }$ (multiplied by an appropriate power of −1) is called the *codifferential*; it is defined in full generality, for any dimension, further in the article below.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The Laplacian can also be seen as a special case of the more general Laplace–deRham operator $\Delta =d\delta +\delta d$ where in three dimensions, $\delta =(-1)^{k}{\star }d{\star }$ is the codifferential for k -forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Any function f is a 0-form, and $\delta f=0$ and so this reduces to the ordinary Laplacian.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] For the 1-form $\varphi$ above, the codifferential is $\delta =-{\star }d{\star }$ and after some straightforward calculations one obtains the Laplacian acting on $\varphi$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] where s is the parity of the signature of the scalar product on *V*, that is, the sign of the determinant of the matrix of the scalar product with respect to any basis.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] For example, if *n* = 4 and the signature of the scalar product is either (+ − − −) or (− + + +) then *s* = −1.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] For Riemannian manifolds (including Euclidean spaces), we always have *s* = 1.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] If n is odd then *k*(*n* − *k*) is even for any k, whereas if n is even then *k*(*n* − *k*) has the parity of k.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] where k is the degree of the element operated on.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The Riemannian metric induces a scalar product on ${\textstyle \bigwedge ^{k}{\text{T}}_{p}^{*}M}$ at each point $p\in M$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] More generally, if M is non-orientable, one can define the Hodge star of a *k*-form as a (*n* – *k*)-pseudo differential form; that is, a differential form with values in the canonical line bundle.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Here $\varepsilon _{j_{1}\dots j_{n}}$ is the Levi-Civita symbol with $\varepsilon _{1\dots n}=1$ , and we implicitly take the sum over all values of the repeated indices $j_{1},\ldots ,j_{n}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The factorial $(n-k)!$ accounts for double counting, and is not present if the summation indices are restricted so that $j_{k+1}<\dots <j_{n}$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The absolute value of the determinant is necessary since it may be negative, as for tangent spaces to Lorentzian manifolds.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The factorial $k!$ is again included to account for double counting when we allow non-increasing indices.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Although one can apply this expression to any tensor $\alpha$ , the result is antisymmetric, since contraction with the completely anti-symmetric Levi-Civita symbol cancels all but the totally antisymmetric part of the tensor.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] It is thus equivalent to antisymmetrization followed by applying the Hodge star.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The most important application of the Hodge star on manifolds is to define the **codifferential** $\delta$ on k -forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The codifferential is not an antiderivation on the exterior algebra, in contrast to the exterior derivative.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The codifferential is the adjoint of the exterior derivative with respect to the square-integrable scalar product: $\langle \!\langle \eta ,\delta \zeta \rangle \!\rangle \ =\ \langle \!\langle d\eta ,\zeta \rangle \!\rangle ,$ where $\zeta$ is a k -form and $\eta$ a $(k\!-\!1)$ -form.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] This property is useful as it can be used to define the codifferential even when the manifold is non-orientable (and the Hodge star operator not defined).
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] (The proper definition of the above requires specifying a topological vector space that is closed and complete on the space of smooth forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The Laplace–deRham operator is given by $\Delta =(\delta +d)^{2}=\delta d+d\delta$ and lies at the heart of Hodge theory.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] The Hodge star sends harmonic forms to harmonic forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] A practical way of finding $\alpha$ is to use cohomotopy operator h , that is a local inverse of $\delta$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] Cohomotopy operator fulfills the following properties: $h^{2}=0,\quad \delta h\delta =\delta ,\quad h\delta h=h$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] This direct sum is another way of saying that the cohomotopy invariance formula is a decomposition of unity, and the projector operators on the summands fulfills idempotence formulas: $(h\delta )^{2}=h\delta ,\quad (\delta h)^{2}=\delta h$ .
[src:exterior-algebra/hodge-star-operator] These results are extension of similar results for exterior derivative.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In multilinear algebra, a **multivector**, sometimes called **Clifford number** or **multor**, is an element of the exterior algebra Λ(*V*) of a vector space V.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A ***k*-vector** is such a linear combination that is *homogeneous* of degree k (all terms are *k*-blades for the same k).
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Depending on the authors, a "multivector" may be either a *k*-vector or any element of the exterior algebra (any linear combination of *k*-blades with potentially differing values of *k*).
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In differential geometry, a *k*-vector is usually a vector in the exterior algebra of the tangent vector space of a smooth manifold; that is, it is an antisymmetric tensor obtained by taking linear combinations of the exterior product of *k* tangent vectors, for some integer *k* ≥ 0.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A differential *k*-form is a *k*-vector in the exterior algebra of the dual of the tangent space, which is also the dual of the exterior algebra of the tangent space.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] For *k* = 0, 1, 2 and 3, *k*-vectors are often called respectively *scalars*, *vectors*, *bivectors* and *trivectors*; they are respectively dual to 0-forms, 1-forms, 2-forms and 3-forms.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The exterior product (also called the wedge product) used to construct multivectors is multilinear (linear in each input), associative and alternating.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The exterior product of *k* vectors or a sum of such products (for a single *k*) is called a grade *k* multivector, or a *k*-vector.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The maximum grade of a multivector is the dimension of the vector space *V*.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Linearity in either input together with the alternating property implies linearity in the other input.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The multilinearity of the exterior product allows a multivector to be expressed as a linear combination of exterior products of basis vectors of *V*.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The exterior product of *k* basis vectors of *V* is the standard way of constructing each basis element for the space of *k*-vectors, which has dimension (*n* *k*) in the exterior algebra of an *n*-dimensional vector space.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The *k*-vector obtained from the exterior product of *k* separate vectors in an *n*-dimensional space has components that define the projected (*k* − 1)-volumes of the *k*-parallelotope spanned by the vectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The square root of the sum of the squares of these components defines the volume of the *k*-parallelotope.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The following examples show that a bivector in two dimensions measures the area of a parallelogram, and the magnitude of a bivector in three dimensions also measures the area of a parallelogram.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Similarly, a three-vector in three dimensions measures the volume of a parallelepiped.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] It is easy to check that the magnitude of a three-vector in four dimensions measures the volume of the parallelepiped spanned by these vectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Properties of multivectors can be seen by considering the two-dimensional vector space *V* = **R**2.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The vertical bars denote the determinant of the matrix, which is the area of the parallelogram spanned by the vectors **u** and **v**.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The magnitude of **u** ∧ **v** is the area of this parallelogram.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Notice that because *V* has dimension two the basis bivector **e**1 ∧ **e**2 is the only multivector in Λ*V*.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The relationship between the magnitude of a multivector and the area or volume spanned by the vectors is an important feature in all dimensions.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Furthermore, the linear functional version of a multivector that computes this volume is known as a differential form.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] More features of multivectors can be seen by considering the three-dimensional vector space *V* = **R**3.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The components of this bivector are the same as the components of the cross product.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The magnitude of this bivector is the square root of the sum of the squares of its components.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] This shows that the magnitude of the bivector **u** ∧ **v** is the area of the parallelogram spanned by the vectors **u** and **v** as it lies in the three-dimensional space *V*.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The components of the bivector are the projected areas of the parallelogram on each of the three coordinate planes.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Notice that because *V* has dimension three, there is one basis three-vector in Λ*V*.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] This shows that the magnitude of the three-vector **u** ∧ **v** ∧ **w** is the volume of the parallelepiped spanned by the three vectors **u**, **v** and **w**.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In higher-dimensional spaces, the component three-vectors are projections of the volume of a parallelepiped onto the coordinate three-spaces, and the magnitude of the three-vector is the volume of the parallelepiped as it sits in the higher-dimensional space.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In this section, we consider multivectors on a projective space *P**n*, which provide a convenient set of coordinates for lines, planes and hyperplanes that have properties similar to the homogeneous coordinates of points, called Grassmann coordinates.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Points in a real projective space *P**n* are defined to be lines through the origin of the vector space **R***n*+1.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] For example, the projective plane *P*2 is the set of lines through the origin of **R**3.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Thus, multivectors defined on **R***n*+1 can be viewed as multivectors on *P**n*.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A convenient way to view a multivector on *P**n* is to examine it in an affine component of *P**n*, which is the intersection of the lines through the origin of **R***n*+1 with a selected hyperplane, such as H: *x**n*+1 = 1.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Lines through the origin of **R**3 intersect the plane E: *z* = 1 to define an affine version of the projective plane that only lacks the points for which *z* = 0, called the points at infinity.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Points in the affine component E: *z* = 1 of the projective plane **P**2 have coordinates **x** = (*x*, *y*, 1).
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A linear combination of two points **p** = (*p*1, *p*2, 1) and **q** = (*q*1, *q*2, 1) defines a plane in **R**3 that intersects E in the line joining **p** and **q**.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Notice that substitution of *α***p** + *β***q** for **p** multiplies this multivector by a constant.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Therefore, the components of **p** ∧ **q** are homogeneous coordinates for the plane through the origin of **R**3.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The set of points **x** = (*x*, *y*, 1) on the line through **p** and **q** is the intersection of the plane defined by **p** ∧ **q** with the plane E: *z* = 1.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] This equation is satisfied by points **x** = *α***p** + *β***q** for real values of α and β.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The three components of **p** ∧ **q** that define the line *λ* are called the Grassmann coordinates of the line.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Because three homogeneous coordinates define both a point and a line, the geometry of points is said to be dual to the geometry of lines in the projective plane.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] This is called the principle of duality.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Three-dimensional projective space *P*3 consists of all lines through the origin of **R**4.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Let the three-dimensional hyperplane, H: *w* = 1, be the affine component of projective space defined by the points **x** = (*x*, *y*, *z*, 1).
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Notice that substitution of α**p** + β**q** + γ**r** for **p** multiplies this multivector by a constant.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Therefore, the components of **p** ∧ **q** ∧ **r** are homogeneous coordinates for the 3-space through the origin of **R**4.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A plane in the affine component H: *w* = 1 is the set of points **x** = (*x*, *y*, *z*, 1) in the intersection of H with the 3-space defined by **p** ∧ **q** ∧ **r**.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The four components of **p** ∧ **q** ∧ **r** that define the plane *λ* are called the Grassmann coordinates of the plane.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Because four homogeneous coordinates define both a point and a plane in projective space, the geometry of points is dual to the geometry of planes.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] These are known as the Plücker coordinates of the line, though they are also an example of Grassmann coordinates.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] where the underline denotes the left complement.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Clifford combined multivectors with the inner product defined on the vector space, in order to obtain a general construction for hypercomplex numbers that includes the usual complex numbers and Hamilton's quaternions.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Clifford's relation retains the anticommuting property for vectors that are perpendicular.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In contrast to the exterior product, the Clifford product of a vector with itself is not zero.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The set of multivectors constructed using Clifford's product yields an associative algebra known as a Clifford algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Inner products with different properties can be used to construct different Clifford algebras.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Multivectors play a central role in the mathematical formulation of physics known as geometric algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] , to emphasize the fact that, in contrast to 0-vectors (scalars), they have "directional properties".
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In 2003 the term *blade* for a multivector that can be written as the exterior product of [a scalar and] a set of vectors was used by C.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Here, by the statement "Any multivector can be expressed as the sum of blades", scalars are implicitly defined as 0-blades.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In geometric algebra, a multivector is defined to be the sum of different-grade *k*-blades, such as the summation of a scalar, a vector, and a 2-vector.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A sum of only *k*-grade components is called a *k*-vector, or a *homogeneous* multivector.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] The highest grade element in a space is called a *pseudoscalar*.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] If a given element is homogeneous of a grade *k*, then it is a *k*-vector, but not necessarily a *k*-blade.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Such an element is a *k*-blade when it can be expressed as the exterior product of *k* vectors.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A geometric algebra generated by a four-dimensional vector space illustrates the point with an example: The sum of any two blades with one taken from the XY-plane and the other taken from the ZW-plane will form a 2-vector that is not a 2-blade.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In a geometric algebra generated by a vector space of dimension 2 or 3, all sums of 2-blades may be written as a single 2-blade.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In the presence of a volume form (such as given an inner product and an orientation), pseudovectors and pseudoscalars can be identified with vectors and scalars, which is routine in vector calculus, but without a volume form this cannot be done without making an arbitrary choice.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In the algebra of physical space (the geometric algebra of Euclidean 3-space, used as a model of (3+1)-spacetime), a sum of a scalar and a vector is called a paravector, and represents a point in spacetime (the vector the space, the scalar the time).
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] A **bivector** is an element of the antisymmetric tensor product of a tangent space with itself.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] In geometric algebra, also, a **bivector** is a grade 2 element (a 2-vector) resulting from the wedge product of two vectors, and so it is geometrically an *oriented area*, in the same way a *vector* is an oriented line segment.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Bivectors are connected to pseudovectors, and are used to represent rotations in geometric algebra.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] As bivectors are elements of a vector space Λ2*V* (where *V* is a finite-dimensional vector space with dim *V* = *n*), it makes sense to define an inner product on this vector space as follows.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] where the Einstein summation convention is being used.
[src:exterior-algebra/multivector] Bivectors play many important roles in physics, for example, in the classification of electromagnetic fields.
